Questions¶

The use of Gephi is permitted for large, complex graph visualization in Sections 2, 3 and 4

Include the whole network visualization and redraw the original networks based on the node-level metrics. And answer the following questions:

a. Write up a paragraph that describes what you learned from the network including: Your assessment of who some of the most important individuals are in the network. Make sure you accurately describe the metrics that were used to determine who is important (e.g., betweenness centrality, degree, eigenvector centrality). Note that some people are important according to one metric (e.g., Betweenness Centrality), while others are important according to another metric (e.g., Degree).

In this network, Valjean has the highest degree centrality, indicating that he is connected to a large # of cahracters. This suggests that Vajean plays a central role in connecting various character in the story. Valjean stands out again as the highest betweenness centrality, signifying that he occupies a critical position in controlling flow of information between characters. Valjean also ranks #1 in Closeness centrality which indicates how quickly a node can reach all other nodes in the network. Gavroche has the highest eigenvector centrality, indicating that he is not only well-connected, but also well connected to other important characters

b. Who is the most influential in terms of Eigenvector centrality? Explain this result.

Gavroche is the most influential in eigenvector centrality, he has the highest score. This metric considers both the number of connections and the importance of those connections. Indicating that Gavroche is well connected, and connected to other important characters.

c. Who has a relatively low degree-centrality (around 0.1315), but high betweenness centrality (among top three)? Explain this result.

Myriel has a low degree-centrality of .131579 yet ranks # 2 in betweeness centrality with a score of 0.176842 might indicate that Myriel may not have a large number of direct connections, or interactions with other nods in the network. Yet plays a critical role in controlling the flow of information or influence between other nodes.

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))  # Increase the figure size for better visibility

labels = {i: i for i in dict(G.nodes).keys()}
degree_centrality = nx.degree_centrality(G)

plt.axis('off')

# Adjust the node size and colormap for better visualization
node_size = [v * 2000 for v in degree_centrality.values()]  # Adjust the multiplier as needed
node_color = list(partition.values())

# Use a different layout algorithm for better node positioning
pos = nx.spring_layout(G, seed=0)

nx.draw_networkx_nodes(
    G,
    pos,
    node_size=node_size,
    cmap=plt.cm.RdYlBu,
    node_color=node_color,
)
nx.draw_networkx_edges(G, pos)
nx.draw_networkx_labels(G, pos, labels, font_size=10)  # Adjust the font_size as needed

plt.show()

In [32]:
from collections import Counter
cluster_sizes = Counter(partition.values())
largest_clusters = cluster_sizes.most_common(2)
for cluster, size in largest_clusters:
    print(f"Cluster {cluster}: {size} nodes")

Cluster 0: 17 nodes
Cluster 2: 16 nodes

D. Your assessment of one specific cluster or subgroup. Now focus on a specific cluster and visualize the subgroup. Provide a brief explanation about the cluster in the contexts of Les Miserable.

In [33]:
cluster_to_visualize = 1

cluster_nodes = [node for node, cluster in partition.items() if cluster == cluster_to_visualize]
subgraph = G.subgraph(cluster_nodes)

pos = nx.spring_layout(subgraph, seed=0)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 12))  # Adjust the figure size as needed
nx.draw(subgraph, pos, with_labels=True, node_size=100, font_size=10, node_color='lightblue', edge_color='gray')

# Show the plot
plt.title(f"Cluster {cluster_to_visualize} Subgraph")
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()
